Check the configuration values and make sure they look sane. Also see if there’s other error messages printing. Sometimes there’s a more helpful error before the stack trace

I’ve seen yagsl fail like this for a few reasons, including

  • Having duplicated motor IDs
  • Having left a module configured the location set to 0,0
  • Having missing/misnamed module configs, which causes yagsl to fail to find one of the module files
  • having the wrong config path entirely such as (eg, “practice bot” instead of “compbot”, but not having the files in deploy).

Thats still attempting to load an old vendor dep somehow.

If you want a full list of dependencies, you can run ./gradlew dependencies in a terminal. There’s likely a 2024 dependency in there somewhere, which is pulling in the 2024 spark max dependency.
